(true);\n        cancelMethod.invoke(thread);\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis branch is only entered for a live `Thread` where:\n\n1. `thread.getClass().getName().startsWith(\"java.util.Timer\")`\n2. The thread class does **not** have OpenJDK’s `newTasksMayBeScheduled` and `queue` fields.\n3. The thread class does have a no-arg `cancel()` method.\n\nOn OpenJDK/GraalVM, `java.util.Timer` uses `java.util.TimerThread`, which has `newTasksMayBeScheduled` and `queue`, so the primary branch is always taken. The current test already covers that reachable branch.\n\nReaching the fallback branch would require simulating an IBM/Harmony-style timer thread such as `java.util.Timer$TimerImpl`. Doing that would require one of the disallowed approaches:\n\n- Creating a fake class in the `java.util` package.\n- Patching/shadowing JDK classes.\n- Generating bytecode dynamically with a `java.util.Timer...` name.\n- Directly reflecting into Tomcat’s private method.\n- Running on a different JDK implementation that naturally provides that timer thread shape.\n\nGiven the rules, the correct outcome is to leave these two implementation-specific compatibility call sites uncovered and preserve the existing public-API coverage for all reachable OpenJDK/GraalVM paths.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0317bfbd632d8e47016a0decb6ec1c819d82d76361313925b0\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 3867, "output": 883, "cacheRead": 65536, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 70286, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1779297449047, "responseId": "resp_0317bfbd632d8e47016a0decabb04c819d99f8a4f0310d140a"}}
